    "Edited Writeup": "Dave lives in Midland, Georgia near Fort Benning. He is married to Marie, daughter of former C4 TAC Captain Bingham, whom he met while serving at Fort Irwin. They have two daughters, ages 26 and 23. The eldest is engaged to be married, lives at home temporarily, and is studying to become a nurse practitioner. The younger recently graduated from Covenant College with a music degree and now teaches in challenging public schools in Columbus, working with students from difficult backgrounds. Both daughters are thriving and each is in a serious relationship with men he respects. His plebe company was G2, graduating from I3. He arrived at West Point with little preparation and felt lost for much of plebe year, but admired the professionalism of the upperclassmen and found their example compelling. He remembers forming deep friendships in G2 and later in I3, where humor and camaraderie sustained him. West Point also sparked his early spiritual awakening, including long evenings in the Cadet Chapel reading his sister's recommended books and beginning to ask serious questions about life, faith, and purpose. His formative years were as an infantry lieutenant and later as a scout platoon leader with the OPFOR at the National Training Center, where the tempo, responsibility, and mentorship from gifted NCOs shaped him as a leader. A signature accomplishment was co-authoring \"The Way,\" the Ranger School devotional, a collaborative project still in circulation and one of the achievements he values most. After 22 years of service, concluding with a staff tour at the Pentagon, he retired and pursued ministry full-time. He attempted to plant a church in a hard part of Columbus, which proved meaningful but exhausting. Today he serves as a chaplain at MercyMed, providing counseling, mental-health support, and social-services assistance. He and his wife also lead a weekly Officer Christian Fellowship group for young lieutenants at Fort Moore. He continues to write and is developing a book on how people grow spiritually through the different relationships in their lives. He values friendship, conversation, and shared experiences more than specific hobbies and appreciates gatherings built around meaningful connection. He would welcome classmates visiting the Columbus area, which he describes as a surprisingly rich place to live. He can be reached at davidbaum@mac.com | 703-895-8852."
