    "Edited Writeup": "Stephen Brooks Brooksie lives in West Chesterfield, New Hampshire. He and his wife have two sons. The eldest graduated from the University of Edinburgh and now works in AI outside London. The younger remains in New Hampshire, interested in technology while working through early-career choices. He comes from a deep New England lineage dating to 1630, with family roots at Lexington-Concord and Navy service through WWII. He met his wife through a Capitol Hill connection. His plebe company was B1, graduating from I2. His memories span a prior-service head start on military skills, the intensity of B-1 hazing, and the infamous \"white socks incident\" that drew the attention of multiple upperclassmen. He played intramural lacrosse until blowing out his ACL a month before graduation, then crossed the stage in a brace. He also recalls the camaraderie of the 5th-floor \"frat,\" working as a track manager, climbing with friends, and mechanical-engineering mentorship from Colonel Barber that tied together mechanical and electrical concepts. His early service included earth-moving and road-building platoons at Fort Belvoir, then a consequential tour at the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers headquarters during Hurricane Katrina and the Loma Prieta earthquake. He consolidated disaster reports for the Chief of Engineers and witnessed the Corps' unique ability to mobilize nationwide assets during crises. He left the Army in 1990 just before stop-loss. He moved into construction management, earned his PE, and then transitioned through multiple engineering and manufacturing leadership roles with Ford and Osram Sylvania. Later he became COO of Littleton Coin Company, an employee-owned retail coin business, using continuous-improvement skills, cross-training, and technical systems expertise to strengthen operations. He regularly attends Johnny Mac golf events and enjoys reconnecting with classmates there. His interests center on outdoor activity, travel, and social gatherings linked to the Northeast, including mountaineering, hiking, and winter environments. He is an introvert who manages energy carefully, credits the Highlands Ability Battery with reshaping his career choices, and believes firmly that \"nice guys don't have to finish last.\" He can be reached at stephen.e.brooks@gmail.com | 603-722-1639."
