    "State": "VA",
    "Metro Area": "Richmond, VA",
    "Edited Writeup": "Robert Bullard Bobby lives in Heathsville, Virginia, where the Potomac River meets the Chesapeake Bay. He has three daughters: Brittany, born 1990 in Fort Sill, Oklahoma, is an Air Force Veteran and lives overseas passionately practicing yoga, pottery, and tea ceremonies; Lauren, born 1992 in Fort Polk, Louisiana, is a nurse and lives in Fairfax, Virginia with her husband (Dennis) and newborn daughter, Carley; and Sophia, born 1998 in Fairfax, Virginia, is an associate scientist for EnviroLogix in Portland, Maine. He is very proud of their independence and enjoys their reunions, though the distance makes those moments even more special. He grew up in St. Petersburg, Florida with a Panamanian mother and a veteran father. His love for the Army started young, influenced by family military service and his older brother's West Point interest. He credits his mother's discipline and early ROTC experience for preparing him well. His plebe company was F4, graduating from I3. His most vivid cadet memory is from Plebe Year when he disastrously cut a Martha Washington sheet cake during lunch. As punishment, he had to salute George Washington's statue and apologize loudly for \"massacring his wife's cake,\" which became a source of great amusement for his company. He also fondly recalls being part of a resistance calisthenics pilot and how his upbringing by a strict Panamanian mother had already prepared him for the fourth-class system. One of his most memorable Army moments was during a chemical training exercise when a CS gas grenade exploded in his hand, giving him a full-face dose and sparking chaos as soldiers thought he'd turned into a gasping zombie. He earned the \"Pink Elephant\" award for that event. He also served as a Battalion FSO in the Third Armored Division during Desert Storm, where he successfully stepped up after another officer couldn't deploy, earning praise from his leadership. After leaving active duty in 1998, he continued to serve in the Army Reserve until 2013, including work as an individual mobilized augmentee at USARPAC in Hawaii, traveling annually from DC. As a defense contractor, he helped design the Worldwide Individual Augmentation System, which became pivotal post-9/11. He also served in various roles as a policy analyst and operations researcher, earned a master's from George Mason, and now works as an Enterprise Architect supporting defense efforts at Fort Belvoir. A lifelong waterman, he loves fishing and boating from his home where his coastal setup and boat access make him ideally suited for fishing trips or water-based gatherings with classmates. He still makes his bed with military precision every morning and maintains a strong sense of self-reflection, encouraging younger leaders to stay grounded, treat people well, and never forget to enjoy life. He can be reached at robert.bullard@yahoo.com | 703-593-1728."
