    "Metro Area": "Norfolk",
    "Edited Writeup": "Crawdad lives in Poquoson, Virginia, just minutes from NASA Langley. He and his wife Tracy have three adult sons. Denver lives in New York City working in and around the entertainment industry with his partner Trey. Davis is a computer engineer for Capital One, working fully remotely from Salt Lake City, where he climbs in summer and skis in winter. Dell, the youngest, recently graduated from Texas State in San Marcos as a theater student and is beginning his own path into the entertainment world. They are empty nesters. Tracy is deeply civic-minded and has served as a local city councilwoman. His plebe company was B1, graduating from I3. As a plebe in B-1, he became known for telling a daily joke at the lunch table after an upperclassman demanded one on the spot. What began as a small survival tactic turned into a year-long ritual, with tables informally \"bidding\" to have him assigned so they could hear the joke of the day, and neighboring tables leaning back to listen. Classmates quietly fed him material, and the routine gave him a positive identity in a tough company. Later in I-3, he remembers the dayroom pool table and an epic three-day weekend drive to St. Pete to see a classmate's girlfriend and play in a Navy soccer game. His Army highlight was his tour as a field artillery officer with the 25th Infantry Division in Hawaii. One defining episode was an unauthorized solo climb from the training area up Mauna Kea to the summit and back, which prompted a near search-and-rescue launch and a furious battalion commander, but also cemented his reputation for endurance and drive. After five years of active duty, he left the Army, used accumulated leave to travel with Tracy, and then entered graduate school at Georgia Tech, where he moved into the young field of atmospheric chemistry, working under a demanding airborne-science PI and flying research missions. That work led directly to NASA, and since 1997 he has been at NASA Langley in Virginia. He is now the senior scientist for airborne atmospheric chemistry for the agency, leading and participating in global aircraft campaigns to understand atmospheric composition and pollution. He enjoys travel and now that Tracy is retired, she often accompanies him on trips related to his NASA work. His West Point foundation—band, math-heavy curriculum, and leadership in hard units—translated directly into leading teams of strong-willed scientists; he notes that getting forty scientists aligned can be as challenging as leading soldiers. Though much of his scientific reputation is strongest overseas in places like Korea and Thailand, he credits the academy's broad education and leadership training for making his NASA career possible. He can be reached at jojatekie@msn.com | 757-876-3011."
