    "Edited Writeup": "Joseph Creekmore resides in Madison, Alabama, where he serves as Government Project Director for the Army's UH-60 Black Hawk Aircrew Trainer simulator program, a role he will retire from at the end of 2026. His cadet highlights include the Plebe Year \"Goat Meat\" food fight in the Mess Hall, surviving a 100-hour slug for walking out of his shoes at Graduation Parade, BP cart races, Spirit Nights before football games, and active involvement in the Baptist Student Union — all while proudly claiming both F-1 and H-4. He branched Aviation, accumulated over 1,000 hours in the UH-1H, served as an exchange officer with the Hungarian Air Force, and completed a MiTT Chief tour in Iraq in 2006-2007 with the 3rd Iraqi Brigade in the Diyala River Valley before leaving active duty after ten years. In the Army Reserve he commanded two brigades — one in Houston and one in Huntsville. His civil service career culminated in designing the Black Hawk Aircrew Trainer and leading production and fielding of 37 devices, six sold to allied nations including Australia, Sweden, and Austria. He and his wife Sue, high school sweethearts who married ten days after graduation, have three children — JP, a software engineer at Google; Maddy, a chemical engineer in the petrochemical industry; and Michael, USMA 2014, a medically retired Captain now working as a process engineer — and six grandchildren. Current interests include golf, travel, and attending sporting events, and he plans in retirement to finish a lifelong trek of the Appalachian Trail. Jody can be reached at 256-464-7098 and jpcreek1963@gmail.com."
