    "State": "DC",
    "Metro Area": "WashingtonDC",
    "Edited Writeup": "Chuck Cushman Chuck lives in Washington, DC. He has had three great cats: Garbo, Danaerys, and Drake.His CTLT rotation with 3rd ACR at Fort Bliss hooked him on armor. He served with 2-66 Armor, 2AD (FWD) in Germany from 87-89, then at Fort Knox with E Troop, 6/12 Cav, and later in the Sosh Department at USMA. In Germany he worked extensively with NATO allies, transitioned from M1 to M1A1, and drove an M1A1 through downtown Hamelin—a signature memory. After nine years he took the early-out offered to his year group. He completed his doctorate at UNC in 1996, then worked in practical politics—campaigns, lobbying, defense consulting—to gain real-world grounding. His civilian career spanned teaching government at Georgetown, training federal officials on congressional relations, and senior academic administration. He served as program director, department chair, and associate dean at GWU from 2001-11, Georgetown from 11-14, Dean of the College of International Security Affairs at NDU from 14-19, associate provost from 19-20, and founding Dean of Academics at the US Naval Community College from 21-present, opening educational doors for USN, USMC, and USCG enlisted personnel. He grew up moving frequently across Massachusetts, Illinois, Florida, Connecticut, and South Carolina because his father designed golf clubs. He adopted the name \"Chuck\" on R-Day as an intentional break from childhood. He joined the speech and debate team where Major Jack Midgley taught him how to think, argue, and lead, skills that shaped his teaching career and made him the \"voice of the TOC\" in Germany. He enjoys conversation, storytelling, and reconnection, and is planning a future that includes time at the beach in Rehoboth and summers in France. He just started a foodie blog, \"What will you have?\" at chucksworldkitchen.com. He still marches everywhere and wears his tar bucket the Monday after every Army-Navy game to irritate Navy colleagues. He can be reached at ccdc20009@gmail.com | 202-904-3887."
