    "Edited Writeup": "Julie Del Giorno Julie is retired and living in Rehoboth Beach, Delaware with no children or grandchildren. She volunteers at her local volunteer fire company, where she serves as Corporate Secretary—interestingly, Station 86. Her plebe company was I3, graduating from C2. She served as a transportation officer supporting the 2/75th Ranger Regiment at Fort Lewis as Platoon Leader and XO, served as Battalion Adjutant during Operation Desert Storm, and commanded a company during Operation Restore Hope in Somalia. After the Army, she worked in various positions in intercollegiate athletics and senior administration at colleges and universities, serving as Chief of Staff for two college presidents. She was hired as the first ever Athletics Integrity Officer at Penn State University in the wake of the Jerry Sandusky scandal. Her strongest cadet memory is the way classmates pulled together to help one another—connections that could be years long or only for a class or two, but when they see each other now, it's as if they were just hanging out in the day room or struggling through Rock Math together. She initiated the Chicks of '86 after learning her sister's Class of '82 women held annual mini-reunions and pushed to replicate it in '86. A 2009 ovarian cancer diagnosis was a key motivator to reconnect with classmates while she still could. She is a primary driver of the Chicks' annual mini-reunion model and values travel-based gatherings built around long unstructured time for talking, relaxing, and shared meals. The group maintains a hard rule of no spouses, partners, or kids to preserve candor and cohesion. She loves being retired, enjoys kayaking, hiking, and travel. She can be reached at jdelgiorno32@gmail.com | 610-554-4061."
