    "Metro Area": "Austin",
    "Edited Writeup": "RD (easily the most popular graduate among his ’86 classmates) lives in Austin, Texas. He has four adult children: his eldest, a University of Texas graduate, lives in Houston with her husband and two young children; his second son, also a Texas graduate, is the global ops manager and designs skis for Icelantic Skis in Golden, Colorado; his third child works for Strafe, a winter/ski outer-wear company based in Aspen/Snowmass; and his youngest daughter is an ER physician assistant in Chicago. RD's military career included deployments to Desert Shield with the 24th Infantry Division, first as the LNO to 2nd Bde, (he appears in the grainy background of a picture first published in Parade Magazine and subsequently in GEN Schwarzkopf’s Book “It Doesn’t take a Hero”). RD subsequently moved to the 24th AVN Brigade to be the TAC OIC just prior to Operation Desert Storm— He later served alongside classmate John Magness with the 160th SOAR in Somalia, RD also deployed as the S3 for 6-6 Cav to Bosnia in ’97, and then later to Kosovo in ’98. RD commanded 4/3 Cavalry Squadron (’03-’04) the first US element to occupy and operate from Al Asad Airbase in the Anbar Province. He played squash and later 150s football, as a cadet in A-4 then C-1 with roommates who have remained friends now for decades. After retiring, he spent 14 years at Dell in Austin. RD currently consults/invests in military/dual-use start up companies. He skis often—helped by two sons working in the ski and outdoor industry—Fashion conscious as he is, RD notes he looks much better kitted in world class gear/clothing (from where his son’s work) than he appears actually skiing down the slopes, or mountain biking the trails with them. He grew up in Huntsville, Alabama, where his father was a high school coach and athletic director whose name adorns the UAH Softball Pressbox. He remains deeply connected to classmates and still attends myriad classmate focused gatherings. He can be reached at robert_douthit@yahoo.com | 512-983-1509."
