    "Edited Writeup": "Alan Hendricks Alan lives in Oscoda, Michigan, with his wife Gina, whom he married in 2000. They adopted Talia, who recently graduated from college and now works as an adoption caseworker. He has two children from a previous marriage: Robert, a high school teacher and administrator with two sons, and Erin, a speech pathologist expecting to deliver another grandson in May. His favorite cadet memory involves white-over-white, knitting needles, kazoos, and the theme from 2001: A Space Odyssey, enough said. A close second involves wheelchair races in Newark Airport; if curious, ask him at the reunion. His Army career began with the 82nd Airborne Division, where he deployed on Golden Pheasant, Just Cause, and Desert Shield/Desert Storm, and commanded the Advanced Airborne School at Fort Bragg. He then branch-transferred to Military Intelligence, spent two years in Korea managing intel information systems, and five years at the National Reconnaissance Office extending national-level intel to the warfighter. Following the post-Cold War RIF, he transitioned to the Army Reserve, where he commanded the last remaining ground-based HF jamming unit in the Army, served as a Defense Foreign Liaison Officer and CGSC instructor, established a special intel unit supporting the National Media Exploitation Center, and deployed with a 10-man Military Transition Team embedded with an Iraqi Army brigade during Operation Iraqi Freedom, experiencing more combat than his previous three deployments combined. He retired in 2009 as a Senior Intelligence Officer at the Defense Intelligence Agency. Simultaneously, Alan built a cybersecurity executive career, holding leadership roles at Netigy, Northrop Grumman, SRA International, and McAfee, culminating as Senior Director of Cybersecurity at DMI, while teaching cybersecurity as an adjunct professor at George Washington University for four to five years. In 2024, he returned all his badges, bought a lake house, and retired from civilian life as well. Current pursuits include backcountry backpacking with only a hammock, cruising his pontoon boat, traveling, including a five-month border-to-border, coast-to-coast trip this year, and hanging out on the deck with a bourbon and cigar. He makes much of his own backpacking gear, excels at pinochle, is a Maker's Mark Ambassador, and may be the only person to have gained tangible financial benefit from plebe poop, winning concert tickets by correctly identifying on a radio call-in show that the U.S. Silver Depository is located at West Point. Alan can be reached at hendricksemail@yahoo.com | 571-447-3938."
