    "Edited Writeup": "Tim McConvery Tim and his wife Michele live in The Villages, Florida. Between them they have six children, four from his first marriage and two stepchildren, who are spread across Florida, Alabama, and Pennsylvania. His oldest son sells cars in Enterprise, Alabama, and has two boys. The second son works as an engineer in Florida. The third son is a firefighter in Dothan, Alabama, with two girls. His oldest daughter lives in Enterprise with her husband and three children. His next daughter has a master's in communication, works for Temple University in Philadelphia with her husband, and is applying to PhD programs. The youngest daughter owns and manages a barbecue restaurant in Enterprise with her husband and has three children. Ten grandchildren in all. Tim was attached to A Company 1-228th Aviation Regiment in Panama in 1989 with a section of his platoon, flying over the jungles and canal before Operation Just Cause. The next year he flew with 5-101st during Desert Storm, attached to the 101st Airborne Division. On the third flight into Iraq the day the ground campaign kicked off, he was forced to crash his Black Hawk—a total loss, but all 19 on board walked away unharmed. He left active duty in 1995 and stayed in the Army Reserve until 2016, instructing at CGSC, commanding a Drill Sergeant Battalion, then commanding an aviation mobilization brigade. Between 1995 and 2000 he worked as an engineer and supervisor in manufacturing, then returned to government service as a civilian for 25 years, ending up as a professor of requirements management at the Warfighting Acquisition University. He remembers going home early in the 1986 season with Joe DePinto and Bill Purcell for a three-day Mets series the year they won the World Seriesand crashing at his house in New Jersey between games. He plays golf, rides bikes, and gets out on the boat whenever he can. He takes his faith seriously as a born again Christian with clear priorities as a Christian first, husband second, father and grandfather third. He can be reached at tim.mcconvery@outlook.com | 334-790-5172."
