    "Town": "APO",
    "State": "AE",
    "Edited Writeup": "Chris lives in Vicenza, Italy with his lovely wife and Desert Shield/Storm pen pal, Melissa. He has one son, Michael, who works as an audio engineer based in Nashville. His plebe company was E3, graduating from D1. His cadet memories include never ceasing to be amazed by the creativity of bored cadets—watching cadets roll a giant snowball and wedge it into a sally port, and the Sosh Show on WKDT cow year when after taps the DJ played Twisted Sister's \"We're Not Gonna Take It\" and the entire Corps blasted their stereo speakers out the barracks windows singing along. He did the Infantry thing for 30 years. His early claim to fame was going AWOL by not reporting to IOAC and going back to his old battalion, 1-327 Infantry in the 101st, so he could deploy with them to Desert Shield/Storm—he didn't get paid for six months for his efforts, but did meet and marry his pen pal, Melissa, so it all worked out. He became a training guy by mid-career, serving as a JRTC and BCTP O/C, commanding 1-19 Infantry at Fort Benning, and doing multiple tours as an advisor in Iraq and Afghanistan, culminating with command of NATO. Training Mission Afghanistan’s Regional Support Command South in Khandahar. The best assignment came at the end of his career when he got to be the senior US liaison officer at British Army HQ in the UK. After doing contract work for the Army, he became a DoD Civilian in 2017 and for the last six years has been in Vicenza, Italy as Deputy G7 for the Southern European Task Force, Africa (SETAF-AF) overseeing the development and management of training exercises in Europe and Africa. He has been skydiving as a hobby since lieutenant days at Fort Campbell and is still very active in the sport with 2,700+ jumps. His cadet car was a VW Beetle, the only one in the cadet parking lot. He parted with it in 1996 but after retiring acquired a 1971 VW Bus that became a second hobby—it's in the care of his cousin, a ‘94 Grad, in Kansas while he's in Italy. He enjoys travel and studying military history. He can be reached at CDRINF@aol.com or +39 347 902-1954"
